===Noun===
{{en-plural noun|head=[[degree]]s of [[comparison]]|sg=degree of comparison}}

# {{context|linguistics|grammar|lang=en}} The [[inflected]] forms of an [[adjective]] that indicate different [[degree]]s of the [[attribute]] the adjective denotes, usually relative to something else; in general, the types of inflection available for an adjective to denote different degrees of its associated attribute; the [[positive#Noun|positive]] (uninflected adjective), [[comparative#Noun|comparative]] and [[superlative#Noun|superlative]] forms.
#: ''The '''degrees of comparison''' of [[good]] are [[good]] (positive), [[better]] (comparative) and [[best]] (superlative).''
#* '''1820''', James Brown, ''An American Grammar'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=Y5Y_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA43&dq=%22degree%7Cdegrees+of+comparison%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3MxUs_QC4rBkgWz_YGwBQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22degree%7Cdegrees%20of%20comparison%22&f=false page 43],
#*: The word ''red'' is an adjective, in the ''dogmatical'' or ''positive'' '''degree of comparison'''.
#* '''1833''', Joseph Hervey Hull, ''English Grammar, by Lectures'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=J2oVAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA55&dq=%22degree%7Cdegrees+of+comparison%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3MxUs_QC4rBkgWz_YGwBQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22degree%7Cdegrees%20of%20comparison%22&f=false page 55],
#*: There are commonly reckoned three '''degrees of comparison''', namely: the positive, comparative and superlative; though, strictly speaking, there are but two degrees, the positive being merely the state of the adjective itself.
#* '''1851''', [[w:Goold Brown|Goold Brown]], Samuel U. Berrian (editor), ''The Grammar of English Grammars'', 10th Edition, [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=q4gSAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA285&dq=%22degree%7Cdegrees+of+comparison%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3MxUs_QC4rBkgWz_YGwBQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22degree%7Cdegrees%20of%20comparison%22&f=false page 285],
#*: Among the '''degrees of comparison''', some have enumerated ''equality''; as when we say, "It is ''as sweet as'' honey."
#* '''2007''', Rodney J. Decker, ''Koine Greek Reader: Selections from the New Testament, Septuagint, and Early Christian Writers'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=lSSIqvEHSvUC&pg=PA205&dq=%22degree%7Cdegrees+of+comparison%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3MxUs_QC4rBkgWz_YGwBQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22degree%7Cdegrees%20of%20comparison%22&f=false page 205],
#*: The '''degrees of comparison''' possible are: positive (''big''), comparative (''bigger''), superlative (''biggest''), and elative (''very big'').

